merican thought. Exploring the connections between these two unlikely interlocutors, the contributors focus on unmasking and understanding the root causes and racially inflected symptoms of various manifestations of cultural malaise. They contemplate the operative warrant for reconstituted conceptions of racial identity and recognize the existential and social recuperative potential of the will to power. In so doing, they simultaneously foster and exemplify a nuanced understanding of what both traditions regard as "the art of the cultural physician." The contributors connote daring scholarly attempts to explicate the ways in which clarifying the critical affinities between Nietzsche and various expressions of African American thought not only enriches our understanding of each, but also enhances our ability to realize the broader ends of advancing the prospects for social and psychological flourishing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAcampora, Christa Davis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Daniel W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, A. Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranklin, A. Todd, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGooding-Williams, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Lewis R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiggins, Kathleen Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPittman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v